The recent seizure of a large ivory shipment from Malawi bound for the Far East, the largest since the 1989 ivory trade ban, highlights the threat to elephant populations.
With only about 10% of contraband detected, the actual amount of poached ivory is staggering.
DNA testing by US scientists aims to trace the origins of illegal ivory, aiding enforcement efforts.
Proposed bans on ivory trade and efforts to protect elephants are crucial, as conservationists work to combat the illegal wildlife trade.
The need for international cooperation and strong enforcement measures is evident to safeguard these majestic creatures.
